      "acceptanceCriteria": "https://uofa.net/morrison/criteria/sqa-mrl2",
      "rationale": "The CFD solver (ANSYS Fluent 2022 R2) is a commercially validated, FDA-recognized software tool with documented software quality assurance processes compliant with ISO 9001:2015. Solver release notes, patch history, and regression test suite results for rotating machinery applications were reviewed and archived. Internal SQA checklist completed per organizational SOP-CFD-001. Version control and audit trail maintained in the project repository. Achieved Gradation 2 exceeds the Gradation 1 requirement for MRL 2."
    },
    {
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorType": "Numerical code verification",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "requiredLevel": 2,
      "achievedLevel": 3,
      "acceptanceCriteria": "https://uofa.net/morrison/criteria/code-verification-mrl2",
      "rationale": "Method of manufactured solutions (MMS) was applied to the incompressible Navier-Stokes solver in the rotating reference frame. Observed spatial order of accuracy p=1.97 is consistent with the theoretical 2nd-order scheme. L2 norm of velocity error decreases monotonically across four mesh refinement levels. Coriolis and centrifugal source term implementations were independently verified. Results documented in validation report VR-CV-2023-01. Achieved Gradation 3 exceeds the Gradation 2 requirement for MRL 2, providing additional confidence in solver correctness."
    },
    {
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorType": "Discretization error",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "requiredLevel": 2,
      "achievedLevel": 2,
      "acceptanceCriteria": "https://uofa.net/morrison/criteria/discretization-error-mrl2",
      "rationale": "Richardson extrapolation performed on three systematically refined hexahedral meshes (2.1M, 6.8M, 18.4M cells) following Celik et al. (2008) best-practice guidelines. Grid convergence index for the primary quantity of interest (normalized index of hemolysis, NIH) at the worst-case operating point (2 LPM, 4500 RPM): GCI_fine = 3.1%. Asymptotic convergence ratio confirmed at 1.02 (target < 1.05). Discretization uncertainty of ±4.2% NIH is within the ±15% model acceptance band. Production mesh of 6.8M cells selected as optimal balance of accuracy and computational cost."
    },
    {
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorType": "Test conditions",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "requiredLevel": 2,
      "achievedLevel": 2,
      "acceptanceCriteria": "https://uofa.net/morrison/criteria/test-conditions-mrl2",
      "rationale": "In-vitro hemolysis experiments and PIV measurements were conducted using the FDA generic centrifugal pump geometry fabricated to ASTM F1841 tolerances. Test fluid (bovine blood, hematocrit 33±2%) was conditioned to 37°C±0.5°C. Flow rates controlled via calibrated Coriolis mass flowmeter (±0.5% accuracy). Rotational speed verified by optical tachometer (±5 RPM). Five operating points (2, 3, 4, 5, 6 LPM at 3500 and 4500 RPM) span the intended clinical use envelope. Test protocol reviewed and approved per institutional biosafety committee. Conditions documented in test report TR-2023-07."
    },
    {
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorType": "Output comparison",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "requiredLevel": 2,
      "achievedLevel": 2,
      "acceptanceCriteria": "https://uofa.net/morrison/criteria/output-comparison-mrl2",
      "rationale": "Predicted NIH values compared against in-vitro measurements across all 5 operating points using the modified hemolysis index protocol (ASTM F1841). Percent error ranges from 3.2% to 14.8%, with all predictions within the pre-specified ±15% acceptance band. Relative hemolysis index (RH) computed against predicate device: RH = 0.82 at worst-case condition, satisfying RH < 1 acceptance criterion. Bland-Altman analysis confirms no systematic bias (mean difference = +1.3% NIH). Uncertainty in experimental NIH measurements (±8% at 95% CI) incorporated into comparison per ASME V&V 40 Section 6."
    },
    {
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorType": "Relevance of the quantities of interest",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "requiredLevel": 2,
      "achievedLevel": 2,
      "acceptanceCriteria": "https://uofa.net/morrison/criteria/qoi-relevance-mrl2",
      "rationale": "The primary quantity of interest — normalized index of hemolysis (NIH, mg/dL) — is the FDA-recognized metric for pump-induced red blood cell damage and is directly linked to the regulatory decision criterion (RH < 1 relative to predicate). Secondary QOIs include volumetric flow-weighted shear stress distribution and exposure time histogram, which are mechanistically linked to the power-law erythrocyte damage model. All QOIs are directly computable from the CFD solution fields and have established experimental measurement protocols. Clinical relevance confirmed by reference to ISO 10993-4 and FDA guidance on blood-contacting device hemolysis."
    },
    {
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorType": "Relevance of the validation activities to the COU",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "requiredLevel": 2,
      "achievedLevel": 2,
      "acceptanceCriteria": "https://uofa.net/morrison/criteria/validation-relevance-mrl2",
      "rationale": "Validation activities were conducted on the identical FDA generic centrifugal pump geometry specified in the COU, at operating conditions that bound the intended clinical use envelope (1.5–6.5 LPM, 3000–5000 RPM). The validation dataset encompasses the worst-case hemolysis operating point identified in the COU. Blood analog fluid properties (viscosity, density) match clinical CPB conditions within 5%. Geometric fidelity of the test article to the computational model confirmed by CMM inspection (dimensional deviations < 0.05 mm). Validation scope is therefore directly applicable to the COU without extrapolation beyond validated conditions."
    },
    {
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorType": "Numerical solver error",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "requiredLevel": 1,
      "achievedLevel": 2,
      "acceptanceCriteria": "https://uofa.net/morrison/criteria/solver-error-mrl2",
      "rationale": "Iterative convergence monitored via residual reduction to 10^-6 for continuity and momentum equations and 10^-5 for turbulence quantities (SST k-omega model). Mass imbalance across inlet/outlet boundaries confirmed < 0.01% at all operating points. Double-precision arithmetic used throughout. Time-averaged quantities extracted after 10 complete impeller revolutions following initial transient. Solver settings documented in simulation protocol SP-CFD-2023-03 and independently reviewed by a second analyst. Achieved Gradation 2 exceeds the Gradation 1 requirement."
    },
    {
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorType": "Use error",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "requiredLevel": 1,
      "achievedLevel": 2,
      "acceptanceCriteria": "https://uofa.net/morrison/criteria/use-error-mrl2",
      "rationale": "Simulation setup reviewed by an independent senior CFD analyst not involved in the primary analysis. Checklist-based review covered geometry import, boundary condition assignment, material property specification, solver settings, and post-processing scripts. All discrepancies identified during review (two minor boundary condition label errors) were corrected prior to production runs. Post-processing scripts version-controlled and unit-tested against analytical solutions. Final simulation inputs archived in the project repository with checksums to prevent inadvertent modification. Achieved Gradation 2 exceeds the Gradation 1 requirement for MRL 2."
    },
    {
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorType": "Model form",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "requiredLevel": 2,
      "achievedLevel": 2,
      "acceptanceCriteria": "https://uofa.net/morrison/criteria/model-form-mrl2",
      "rationale": "The SST k-omega turbulence model was selected based on its established performance for rotating machinery internal flows with adverse pressure gradients, as documented in the FDA critical path hemolysis benchmark study (Hariharan et al., 2011). The Giersiepen power-law erythrocyte damage model (C=3.62×10^-5, alpha=2.416, beta=0.785) is the standard for regulatory hemolysis prediction per FDA guidance. Non-Newtonian blood rheology modeled using the Carreau-Yasuda model with parameters fit to CPB-range hematocrit data. Model form assumptions documented and justified in modeling report MR-2023-02. Sensitivity of NIH predictions to turbulence model choice assessed (±12% variation across SST, realizable k-epsilon, and RSM)."
    },
    {
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorType": "Model inputs",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "requiredLevel": 2,
      "achievedLevel": 2,
      "acceptanceCriteria": "https://uofa.net/morrison/criteria/model-inputs-mrl2",
      "rationale": "All model input parameters (geometry dimensions, fluid properties, boundary conditions, damage model coefficients) sourced from calibrated measurements or peer-reviewed literature with documented uncertainty. Pump geometry digitized from CMM measurements of the physical test article (dimensional uncertainty ±0.03 mm). Fluid viscosity and density measured at 37°C using calibrated rheometer and densitometer respectively. Inlet velocity profile derived from Womersley solution for the measured flow waveform. Parametric sensitivity analysis performed on the five most influential inputs (impeller clearance gap, blood viscosity, damage model exponents alpha and beta, inlet turbulence intensity), confirming NIH sensitivity within ±18% across ±2-sigma input ranges."
    },
    {
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorType": "Test samples",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "factorStatus": "scoped-out",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "https://uofa.net/morrison/criteria/test-samples-mrl2",
      "rationale": "The Test samples factor addresses variability in biological test specimens used for validation experiments. For this COU, hemolysis validation experiments used pooled bovine blood from a single certified supplier (HemoSource Inc., lot BV-2023-14) prepared to a standardized protocol (hematocrit 33±2%, leukocyte-depleted). The use of a single blood lot is consistent with ASTM F1841 standard practice for hemolysis index testing and is accepted by FDA for Class II CPB device submissions at MRL 2. Inter-lot variability in bovine blood hemolytic susceptibility is a recognized source of uncertainty; however, at MRL 2 with medium model influence, the ASME V&V 40 framework permits scoping out this factor when: (1) the experimental protocol follows a recognized consensus standard (ASTM F1841), (2) the measurement uncertainty budget explicitly includes a ±8% NIH component attributed to biological variability based on published inter-lot variability data (Down et al., 2019, J. Biomech. Eng.), and (3) the acceptance criterion RH < 1 incorporates a 15% safety margin relative to the predicate device. All three conditions are satisfied. This factor is therefore formally scoped out of the credibility assessment with the understanding that its contribution to total uncertainty is bounded and accounted for in the output comparison factor. Formal multi-lot or human blood validation is deferred to a future MRL 3 assessment if the device advances to a higher-risk indication."
    },
    {
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorType": "Equivalency of input parameters",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "factorStatus": "scoped-out",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "https://uofa.net/morrison/criteria/equivalency-inputs-mrl2",
      "rationale": "The Equivalency of input parameters factor evaluates whether the input parameters used in the computational model are equivalent to those present in the actual clinical use environment. For this COU, the primary potential non-equivalency is between the in-vitro test conditions (controlled laboratory flow loop, bovine blood analog, rigid pump housing) and the clinical CPB circuit (patient-specific hemodynamics, human blood, compliant tubing interactions, variable perfusionist settings). At MRL 2 with medium model influence, full equivalency demonstration is not required; instead, the assessment team has: (1) documented all known input parameter differences between the simulation/validation environment and the clinical COU in a formal equivalency gap analysis (EGA-2023-01); (2) quantified the sensitivity of NIH predictions to the three largest identified gaps — inlet flow waveform shape (±6% NIH), blood temperature variation 35–38°C (±3% NIH), and housing compliance (±2% NIH) — through targeted sensitivity simulations; and (3) confirmed that the combined worst-case sensitivity of ±11% NIH does not alter the regulatory conclusion (RH = 0.82 remains below 1.0 even under combined adverse conditions, yielding RH_worst = 0.91). Given that the residual non-equivalency is bounded, quantified, and does not affect the regulatory decision, and given that the ASME V&V 40 MRL 2 requirements for this factor are satisfied by documented gap analysis with bounded sensitivity, this factor is formally scoped out from further assessment. Comprehensive equivalency demonstration using patient-matched boundary conditions would be required at MRL 3 for a higher-consequence indication."
    }
  ],
  "hasWeakener": [],
  "hasDecisionRecord": {
    "id": "https://uofa.net/morrison/decision/cou1-accepted-2026",
    "type": "DecisionRecord",
    "actor": "https://uofa.net/morrison/org/computational-biomechanics-lab",
    "role": "Credibility assessment team",
    "outcome": "Accepted",
    "rationale": "The credibility assessment for COU1 (CFD hemolysis prediction for Class II CPB device at MRL 2) is accepted based on the following structured evidence: (1) All 11 assessed credibility factors meet or exceed their required gradation levels for MRL 2. Notably, Software quality assurance (Gradation 2 vs. required 1), Numerical code verification (Gradation 3 vs. required 2), Numerical solver error (Gradation 2 vs. required 1), and Use error (Gradation 2 vs. required 1) exceed minimum requirements, providing additional assurance margins. (2) The two scoped-out factors (Test samples and Equivalency of input parameters) are supported by thorough documented rationale demonstrating that their contributions to prediction uncertainty are bounded, quantified, and incorporated into the output comparison uncertainty budget. The residual uncertainty from both scoped-out factors (±11% NIH combined) does not alter the regulatory conclusion. (3) The primary regulatory acceptance criterion — relative hemolysis index RH < 1 — is satisfied at all five operating points, with worst-case RH = 0.82, providing an 18% margin relative to the predicate device. Under combined worst-case sensitivity assumptions, RH_worst = 0.91, still satisfying RH < 1. (4) Discretization error is rigorously characterized (GCI_fine = 3.1%, within ±4.2% NIH), and iterative convergence is confirmed at all operating points. (5) Validation activities were conducted on the identical pump geometry under bounding clinical operating conditions, with all NIH predictions within the pre-specified ±15% acceptance band. (6) The provenance chain from raw experimental data through validation results to this credibility assessment is complete and traceable. The model is therefore credible for its intended use: identifying worst-case hemolysis operating conditions and confirming RH < 1 for a Class II CPB device at MRL 2.",
    "decidedAt": "2026-04-19T00:00:00Z"
  },
